  <thing id="xFreezSpit" name="Freezing Spittle" description="Three times per day, an ice troll can spit a disgusting glob of frigid slime with a range of 20 feet. The troll must make a ranged touch attack to hit. The target takes 1d4 points of cold damage and must succeed on a Fortitude save (DC 17) or be nauseated for 1 round. The saving throw is Constitution-based. An ice troll sometimes uses its freezing spittle to extinguish a flame carried by its enemies, such as a lantern or a torch. In this case, the spittle deals no damage to the target, and the bearer may attempt to negate the effect with a Reflex save (DC 17)." compset="Special" summary="3/day, spit freezing goo, 20ft rng R. Touch 1d4 could can extinguish fire.">
    <fieldval field="hTotal" value="3"/>
    <usesource source="UnApproach"/>
    <tag group="Helper" tag="ShowCharge"/>
    <tag group="Helper" tag="ShowSpec"/>
    <tag group="AbilType" tag="Super"/>
    <eval phase="UserPostAt" priority="10000"><![CDATA[~ DC of Replicative Rot HD + 10 + CHA
      var DC as number
      DC = herofield[tHitDice].value + 7 + hero.child[aCON].field[aModBonus].value

      field[livename].text = "Freezing Spittle (F" & DC & ")"]]></eval>
    </thing>
  <thing id="tmTelthor" name="Telthor" description="Telthors are spirit animals or people native to Rashemen, particularly those who died defending the land. Incorporeal and ghostly, they are still formidable opponents.\n\nMany places in Rashemen have guardian spirits, and some trees, rocks, and rivers have them as well. These spirits are the telthors, and they take a form appropriate to what they are guarding. For example, a mountain may have a telthor dire bear guardian, a forest might have a telthor dire wolf guardian, and a spring might have a telthor hawk guardian. Large places or very Important sites might have multiple telthors, each responsible for a part of the site but working together against a foe that threatens them all.\n\nEach berserker lodge of the Rashemi barbarians has a spirit totem, and usually the lodge itself is watched over by a telthor of that kind.\n\nRashemen is rich in untapped spirit magic, and sometimes in places where people have died defending the land, an echo in the sleeping spiritual energy grants a person a semblance of life as a telthor. Normally these people are warriors, fighters, or barbarians, but sometimes a spellcaster can become a telthor. These spirits watch over the battlegrounds where they died, alert for other invaders or those who would despoil their resting places and those of their slain allies. If a creature who became a telthor is brought back from the dead, the telthor vanishes and the newly raised person has no memories of that spirit existence." compset="Template" uniqueness="unique">
    <fieldval field="cLevelAdj" value="+2"/>
    <usesource source="UnApproach"/>
    <bootstrap thing="xFly">
      <autotag group="Value" tag="1"/>
      </bootstrap>
    <bootstrap thing="xBoundLand"></bootstrap>
    <bootstrap thing="xNativeEmp"></bootstrap>
    <bootstrap thing="xTelthTele"></bootstrap>
    <bootstrap thing="lRashemi"></bootstrap>
    <eval phase="PostAttr" priority="20000" index="3">~ We add our dex to hit with melee, since we are incorporeal
   hero.child[Attack].field[tAtkMelee].value += hero.child[aDEX].field[aModBonus].value

~ A telthor looses its natural armor bonus but gains a deflection equal to what its natural armor was.

var armorBon as number
armorBon = hero.child[ArmorClass].field[tACNatural].value

hero.child[ArmorClass].field[tACDeflect].value = maximum(hero.child[ArmorClass].field[tACDeflect].value, armorBon)

hero.child[ArmorClass].field[tACNatural].value = hero.child[ArmorClass].field[tACNatural].value - hero.child[ArmorClass].field[tACNatural].value</eval>
    <eval phase="First" priority="5000" index="2">~ Telthors are incorporeal, NO STRENGTH
      perform hero.child[aSTR].assign[Helper.NoScore]</eval>
    <eval phase="PostLevel" priority="10000"><![CDATA[
      var result as number

      ~ Set our fly speed
        var speed as number
        speed = hero.child[Speed].field[tSpeed].value * 2
        hero.child[xFly].field[Value].value = maximum(hero.child[xFly].field[Value].value, speed)

~ If it has an Average Maneuverability or better do nothing, otherwise its maneuverability becomes poor.
      if (hero.child[xFly].tagis[Maneuver.Average] + hero.child[xFly].tagis[Maneuver.Good] + hero.child[xFly].tagis[Maneuver.Perfect] <> 0) then
        done
      else
        result = hero.child[xFly].delete[Maneuver.?]
        result = hero.child[xFly].assign[Maneuver.Poor]
     endif]]></eval>
    </thing>
  <thing id="xBoundLand" name="Bound to the Land" description="A telthor is tied to the place it guards and is weakened if it moves more than 1 mile from that place. Outside of this area, it takes 1 point of damage every minute. This damage ends immediately if it enters its home area again. Telthors can sense the boundaries of their territory and normally do not leave them except to warn others of danger. Rashemen legends tell of telthors that traveled miles to warn the hathrans of an invasion and then died from the pain of separation before they could be healed." compset="Special" summary="Tied to a specific location, may not go more than a mile without 1dmg/minute.">
    <usesource source="UnApproach"/>
    <tag group="Helper" tag="ShowSpec"/>
    <tag group="AbilType" tag="Super"/>
    </thing>
  <thing id="xNativeEmp" name="Native Animal Empathy" description="Telthors can communicate and empathize with animals of their kind. This gives them a +4 bonus on checks to influence the animal&apos;s attitude and allows the communication of simple concepts and (if the animal is friendly) commands, such as &quot;friend,&quot; &quot;enemy,&quot; &quot;flee,&quot; and &quot;attack.&quot; A humanoid telthor chooses one kind of animal for its empathic bond and gains this ability for that kind of animal only." compset="Special" summary="Empathy with animals of their kind, +4 to checks to influence attitude.">
    <usesource source="UnApproach"/>
    <tag group="Helper" tag="ShowSpec"/>
    <tag group="AbilType" tag="Extra"/>
    </thing>
  <thing id="xTelthTele" name="Telthor Telepathy" description="Telthors can communicate with one another telepathically, regardless of language, at a range of 100 feet." compset="Special" summary="Telepathy with other telthors upto 100ft regardless of language.">
    <usesource source="UnApproach"/>
    <tag group="AbilType" tag="Super"/>
    </thing>
  <thing id="fBattJump" name="Battle Jump" description="You know how to launch a devastating attack from above by dropping onto your opponent.\n\n{b}REGION:{/b} Taer.\n{b}Prerequisit:{/b} Region (Icerim Mountains) OR Knowledge: Local [Rashemen] 2\n\n{b}Benefit:{/b} You can execute a charge by simply dropping from a height of at least 5 feet above your opponent. For example, a ledge 10 feet above the floor of a cavern would suffice for jumping on a Medium-sized creature, while a ledge 15 feet high is required for a jumping on a Large creature. You can&apos;t jump from more than 30 feet above your opponent, nor can you effectively battle jump while under the influence of a fly or levitate spell or effect, as you have to hurl yourself down on your foe. If you hit, you can choose either to deal double damage with a melee weapon or natural attack or to attempt a trip attack. You are treated as one size category larger than normal if you try to trip your opponent with the battle jump. After you attack, you take falling damage as normal for the distance you jumped. You are entitled to a Jump check (DC 15) to take less damage, as if you had fallen 10 feet less than you actually did. If you fail this Jump check, you fall prone 5 feet from your opponent. You can also use Battle Jump to begin a grapple attempt instead of making a normal attack. If you do, you are treated as one size category larger than normal for the first grapple check following the battle jump.\n\n{b}Normal:{/b} Anybody can try to jump down on an enemy, but it is not considered a charge, and they do not gain double damage or the size bonus for the ensuing attack." compset="Feat" summary="You launch a devastating attack from above by dropping onto your opponent." uniqueness="useronce">
    <usesource source="UnApproach"/>
    <tag group="BonusFor" tag="Fighter"/>
    <tag group="Helper" tag="ShowSpec"/>
    <tag group="fCategory" tag="General"/>
    </thing>
  <thing id="fDrawLand" name="Draw from the Land" description="You can draw strength and sustenance from the land itself.\n\n{b}Prerequisite:{/b} Ethran.\n\n{b}REGION:{/b} Rashemen OR Knowledge: Local [Rashemen] 2\n\n{b}Benefit:{/b} Before resting, you may draw upon the power of the land to revitalize your body and mind. This allows you to recover 2 hit points per day of light activity, or 4 hit points per level for each day of complete rest, and 2 ability score points per day, or 4 ability score points for each day of complete rest. This stacks with the benefits of long-term care provided by someone with the Heal skill (see Chapter 5: Skills in the {i}Player&apos;s Handbook{/i}). You may also use the energy of the land to fuel your body&apos;s need for food and water. This gives you a +10 bonus on Constitution checks made to avoid subdual damage from hunger and thirst (see Starvation and Thirst Dangers in Chapter 3: Running the Game in the {i}DUNGEON MASTER&apos;s Guide{/i}). Finally, you may use the power of the land to refresh your mind and body as a supplement to sleep. You require half as much sleep as normal (although you still have to rest a full 8 hours to prepare spells or regain spell slots). Outside of Rashemen, you must make a Concentration check (DC 10 + 2 per 100 miles from the border of Rashemen) to activate this ability. If you fail, you cannot retry for 1 day." compset="Feat" summary="Grants increased benefit from resting and passive healing bonus." uniqueness="useronce">
    <usesource source="UnApproach"/>
    <tag group="Helper" tag="ShowSpec"/>
    <tag group="fCategory" tag="General"/>
    <exprreq message="Ethran required."><![CDATA[#hasfeat[fEthran] <> 0]]></exprreq>
    </thing>
  <thing id="fEttercapB" name="Ettercap Berserker" description="The intense physical training required to join your lodge has made you tougher.\n\n{b}Prerequisite:{/b} Ability to rage, membership in the Ettercap berserker lodge (see Berserker Lodges in Chapter 10: Rashemen).\n{b}REGION:{/b} Rashemen OR Knowledge: Local [Rashemen] 2\n\n{b}Benefit:{/b} You gain a +2 bonus on saving throws against poison. When raging, you gain a +6 bonus to Constitution. During a greater rage, you instead gain a +8 bonus to Constitution.\n{b}Normal:{/b} A character in a rage gains a +4 bonus to Constitution. A character in a greater rage gains a +6 bonus to Constitution." compset="Feat" summary="+4 vs Poisons, +6 con in a rage and +8 in a Greater Rage." uniqueness="useronce">
    <usesource source="UnApproach"/>
    <tag group="BonusFor" tag="Fighter"/>
    <tag group="Helper" tag="ShowSpec"/>
    <tag group="fCategory" tag="General"/>
    <exprreq message="Rage required."><![CDATA[picklives[cBbnRage] <> 0]]></exprreq>
    </thing>
  <thing id="fExtendRag" name="Extended Rage" description="Your rage lasts longer than it normally would.\n\n{b}Prerequisite:{/b} Ability to rage\n{b}Benefit:{/b} Each of your rages lasts an additional 5 rounds beyond its normal duration.\n\n{b}Special:{/b} You can take this feat multiple times, and the additional rounds stack." compset="Feat" summary="Your rage lasts 5 rounds beyond its normal duration.  Can be taken more than once.,">
    <usesource source="UnApproach"/>
    <tag group="fCategory" tag="General"/>
    <tag group="Helper" tag="ShowSpec"/>
    <exprreq message="Rage required."><![CDATA[picklives[cBbnRage] <> 0]]></exprreq>
    </thing>
  <thing id="fGrStagBer" name="Great Stag Berserker" description="Your fighting style employs aggressive charges in the manner of your lodge&apos;s totem animal.\n\n{b}Prerequisite:{/b} Ability to rage, membership in the Great Stag berserker lodge (see Berserker Lodges in Chapter 10: Rashemen).\n{b}REGION:{/b} Rashemen OR Knowledge: Local [Rashemen] 2\n\n{b}Benefit:{/b} When using the charge action, you may gain a +4 bonus on your attack roll and take a -4 penalty to your AC for 1 round.\n{b}Normal:{/b} A charging character normally has a +2 bonus on attacks and a -2 penalty to AC for 1 round." compset="Feat" summary="Grants +4 to attack roll and -4 penalty to AC during a charge action." uniqueness="useronce">
    <usesource source="UnApproach"/>
    <tag group="BonusFor" tag="Fighter"/>
    <tag group="fCategory" tag="General"/>
    <tag group="Helper" tag="ShowSpec"/>
    <exprreq message="Rage required."><![CDATA[picklives[cBbnRage] <> 0]]></exprreq>
    </thing>
  <thing id="fIceTrBerz" name="Ice Troll Berserker" description="When raging, your skin becomes very thick and tough like the ice trolls that plague parts of your homeland.\n\n{b}Prerequisite:{/b} Ability to rage, Constitution 13, membership in the Ice Troll berserker lodge (see Berserker Lodges in Chapter 10: Rashemen).\n{b}REGION:{/b} Rashemen OR Knowledge: Local [Rashemen] 2\n\n{b}Benefit:{/b} When raging, you gain a +2 natural armor bonus to AC. During a greater rage this natural armor bonus increases to +4." compset="Feat" summary="+2 Natural Armor while in rage or +4 Natural Armor in Greater Rage." uniqueness="useronce">
    <usesource source="UnApproach"/>
    <tag group="BonusFor" tag="Fighter"/>
    <tag group="fCategory" tag="General"/>
    <exprreq message="Rage required."><![CDATA[picklives[cBbnRage] <> 0]]></exprreq>
    <exprreq message="Constitution 13 required."><![CDATA[child[aCON].field[aFinalVal].value <= 13]]></exprreq>
    </thing>
  <thing id="fOwlbeaBer" name="Owlbear Berserker" description="Your fighting style emulates the owlbear, the totem beast of your berserker lodge.\n\n{b}Prerequisite:{/b} Ability to rage, Strength 13, membership in the Owlbear berserker lodge (see Berserker Lodges in Chapter 10: Rashemen).\n\n{b}REGION:{/b} Rashemen or Knowledge: Local [Rashemen] 2\n\n{b}Benefit:{/b} When grappling, you can make an unarmed attack to deal 1d6 points of normal damage with a successful grapple check. You do not suffer the usual -4 penalty for dealing normal damage.\n\n{b}Normal:{/b} Characters who do not have this feat can deal 1d3 points of subdual damage, or normal damage at a -4 penalty on the grapple check.\n\n{b}Special:{/b} Characters with this feat may choose the Improved Grapple feat even if they don&apos;t meet the other prerequisites for Improved Grapple." compset="Feat" summary="Deal 1d6 damage unarmed and do not take -4 penalty to do so." uniqueness="useronce">
    <usesource source="UnApproach"/>
    <tag group="fCategory" tag="General"/>
    <tag group="Helper" tag="ShowSpec"/>
    <tag group="BonusFor" tag="Fighter"/>
    <exprreq message="Rage required."><![CDATA[picklives[cBbnRage] <> 0]]></exprreq>
    <exprreq message="Strength 13 required."><![CDATA[child[aSTR].field[aFinalVal].value <= 13]]></exprreq>
    </thing>
  <thing id="fRashEleSu" name="Rashemi Elemental Summoning" description="You may summon Rashemen&apos;s native elementals in any situation where you could summon an air or earth elemental.\n\n{b}Prerequisite:{/b} Spellcaster Level 5\n\n{b}Benefit:{/b} When casting a spell that summons air or earth elementals, you may choose to summon an orglash or thomil instead. (See the Orglash and Thomil entries in Chapter 6: Monsters of the East) For example, if you cast {i}summon monster V{/i}, which can summon a medium elemental, you may summon an orglash or thomil using a medium elemental as the base creature. If you cast {i}elemental swarm{/i}, you could opt to summon orglashes or thomils based on large, huge, and greater air or earth elementals. Altering the spell in this manner does not change any other aspects of the spell. You may use this ability outside of Rashemen." compset="Feat" summary="Augment Summonings of Air/Earth elementals with creatures of the East." uniqueness="useronce">
    <usesource source="UnApproach"/>
    <tag group="fCategory" tag="General"/>
    <tag group="Helper" tag="ShowSpec"/>
    </thing>
  <thing id="fSnTigerBe" name="Snow Tiger Berserker" description="You have learned how to pounce on your foes, much like your totem spirit.\n\n{b}Prerequisite:{/b} Ability to rage, Dexterity 13, membership in the Snow Tiger berserker lodge (see Berserker Lodges in Chapter 10: Rashemen).\n{b}REGION:{/b} Rashemen OR Knowledge: Local [Rashemen] 2\n\n{b}Benefit:{/b} You may make a full attack as part of a charge action, but only if you are armed with a light weapon. (If you have light weapons in both hands, you may strike with both under the normal rules for fighting with two weapons.)\n{b}Normal:{/b} Characters without this feat may make only one attack as part of a charge action." compset="Feat" summary="You can make a full attack as part of a charge action." uniqueness="useronce">
    <usesource source="UnApproach"/>
    <tag group="BonusFor" tag="Fighter"/>
    <tag group="fCategory" tag="General"/>
    <tag group="Helper" tag="ShowSpec"/>
    <exprreq message="Rage required."><![CDATA[picklives[cBbnRage] <> 0]]></exprreq>
    <exprreq message="Dexterity 13 required."><![CDATA[child[aDEX].field[aFinalVal].value <= 13]]></exprreq>
    </thing>
  <thing id="fVremTrain" name="Vremyonni Training" description="[General]\n\nYou have had more than the typical amount of training with the vremyonni, the Old Ones who research spells and craft magic items for the Witches of Rashemen.\n\n{b}Prerequisite:{/b} Able to cast 1st-level spells.\n{b}REGION:{/b} Rashemen OR Knowledge: Local [Rashemen] 2\n\n{b}Benefit:{/b} You gain a +2 bonus on Knowledge (arcana) and Spellcraft checks." compset="Feat" summary="You gain +2 Knowledge (arcana) and Spellcraft checks." uniqueness="useronce">
    <usesource source="UnApproach"/>
    <tag group="fCategory" tag="General"/>
    </thing>
  <thing id="fWolfBerse" name="Wolf Berserker" description="You have studied the fighting style of the wolf and employ its tactics in combat.\n\n{b}Prerequisite:{/b} Ability to rage, membership in the Wolf berserker lodge (see Berserker Lodges in Chapter 10: Rashemen).\n\n{b}REGION:{/b} Rashemen OR Knowledge: Local [Rashemen] 2\n\n{b}Benefit:{/b} You gain a +4 bonus on trip attacks and on checks to resist an opponent&apos;s trip attacks.\n\n{b}Special:{/b} Characters with this feat may choose the {i}Improved Trip{/i} feat even if they don&apos;t meet the other prerequisites for Improved Trip." compset="Feat" summary="+4 Bonus to trip attacks and checks to resist opponent&apos;s trip attacks." uniqueness="useronce">
    <usesource source="UnApproach"/>
    <tag group="BonusFor" tag="Fighter"/>
    <tag group="fCategory" tag="General"/>
    <tag group="Helper" tag="ShowSpec"/>
    <exprreq message="Rage required."><![CDATA[picklives[cBbnRage] <> 0]]></exprreq>
    </thing>
  <thing id="fWoodwise" name="Woodwise" description="You ignore hampered movement penalties from naturally occuring moderate or heavy undergrowth.\n\n{b}Prerequisite:{/b} Elf (the Misty Vale), Or Star elf (Sildeyuir) or Volodni (the Forest of Lethyr)\n\n{b}Benefit:{/b} You ignore hampered movement penalties from naturally occurring light or heavy undergrowth ( you are still hampered by magically enhanced brush and plants.) When Fighting in wooded areas, You gain a +1 dodge bonus ot Armor class.\n\n{b}Normal:{/b} A character without this feat spends 2 squares of movement to thravel through light undergrowth, and 4 squares to travel through heavy undergrowth, and gains no defensive bonus for fighting in woodlands." compset="Feat" summary="Ignore movement pen from natural light/heavy undergrowth. +1 dodge in woods.">
    <usesource source="UnApproach"/>
    <tag group="Helper" tag="ShowSpec"/>
    <tag group="fCategory" tag="General"/>
    </thing>
  <thing id="cHelpThs" name="Thayan Slaver" description="Thayan slavers are cruel marauders who use their awful abilities to abduct creatures and then break their wills. They are experts at creating docile slaves who obey their masters without question.\n\nMost Thayan slavers start out as rogues, but they can come from any class other than paladin. Evil sorcerers and wizards sometimes become Thayan slavers to more easily handle assistants and even subjects for their wicked experiments. Some evil fighters and barbarians find the prestige class is a natural extension of their aggression, as well as expanding their treasure options to include other people. Bards and rangers are less likely to take up such a prestige class, and there are few druids who would consider it.\n\nThayan slavers can be found throughout Faer&#251;n, wherever slaves are traded. Sometimes they work or travel incognito, especially in places in which slavery is outlawed. Of course, Thay is filled with all sorts of Thayan slavers, many of whom work together in the great slave markets of Bezantur, Tyraturos, and Eltabbar." compset="ClassHelp" uniqueness="unique">
